Area: Madison; Marshall; Jackson; DeKalb; Moore; Lincoln; Franklin
Description:
['Significant reductions in visibility are expected in the higher
terrain of northeast Alabama and southern Middle Tennessee this
morning, due to a layer of very low stratus clouds across the region.
Locations above 1000 ft, including Lookout Mountain, Sand Mountain,
and the Cumberland Plateau, will experience widespread visibility
reductions to less than one quarter of a mile.', 'Motorists are urged to drive with extreme caution. Use low beams,
reduce driving speed, and allow for plenty of room between you and
other cars.', 'Visibility conditions will begin to improve around 10 AM CST.']

Area: Glacier Bay; Eastern Chichagof Island; Cape Decision to Salisbury Sound Coastal Area; Eastern Baranof Island and Southern Admiralty Island; Juneau Borough and Northern Admiralty Island
Description:
['An atmospheric river Thursday night through Saturday night will
bring very heavy rain, warming temperatures, rising snow levels,
and a threat of flooding to Juneau, Sitka, Glacier Bay, eastern
Chichagof Island, Admiralty Island, and the rest of Baranof Island.
A Flood Watch is now in effect for the region.', 'A short break is possible Thursday before heavy rain starts
Thursday night and persists for much of the weekend. Rainfall
amounts of 4 to 6 inches are possible from Thursday evening
through Saturday night. Snow levels are forecast to rise to 3,000
around Juneau and Glacier Bay to 7,000 feet on Baranof Island.
Heavy rain along with a melting mountain snowpack will increase
the risk of minor flooding issues. Please stay tuned to local
updates should further flood bulletins be issued.']

Area: Dixon Entrance to Cape Decision Coastal Area; Southern Inner Channels; Misty Fjords
Description:
['An atmospheric river will impact the central and northern
Panhandle this weekend, but could potentially drop south at times
across the southern Panhandle. Expect warming temperatures,
breezy conditions, rising snow levels, and the possibility of
heavy rain during some periods through this weekend. Rain may
become heavy briefly Thursday night before lifting north Friday.
Heavy rain could reappear Saturday night. The current forecast is
for rainfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches from Thursday evening
through Sunday, with the heaviest precipitation likely Saturday
night. Snow levels are forecast to rise from 3,000 in Misty
Fjords, to 6,000 feet around Ketchikan, to as much as 8,000 feet
on Prince of Wales Island. Rain along with a melting mountain
snowpack will increase the risk of minor flooding issues. Should
confidence increase in the possibility of flooding, a flood watch
could be issued in future.']

Area: Cape Fairweather to Cape Suckling Coastal Area; Salisbury Sound to Cape Fairweather Coastal Area
Description:
['An atmospheric river late this week into the weekend will bring
very heavy rain, warming temperatures, rising snow levels, and a
threat of flooding. A Flood Watch is now in effect for the
region.', '
A short break is possible Thursday before heavy rain starts
Thursday night and persists for much of the weekend. Rainfall
amounts of 6 to 8 inches are possible from Thursday evening
through Saturday night for Yakutat, Elfin Cove, and Pelican. Snow
levels are forecast to rise to 3,000 to 6,000 feet. Heavy rain
along with a melting mountain snowpack will increase the risk of
minor flooding issues. Rain over deep snow on top of structures
and rooftops could challenge load limits across Yakutat. Please
stay tuned to local updates should further flood bulletins be
issued.']

Area: Taiya Inlet and Klondike Highway; Haines Borough and Lynn Canal
Description:
['An atmospheric river late this week into the weekend will bring
warming temperatures, rising snow levels, the potential for
accumulating snow changing to heavy rain, and the possibility of
flooding. Please review the Flood Watch now in effect for Upper
Lynn Canal.', 'A short break in the weather is possible Thursday afternoon
through Thursday evening before heavy precipitation moves in
Thursday night. Precipitation will be mainly rain at sea level.
Precipitation begins as snow along the highways near the border
and will hang on longer along the South Klondike Highway. Rainfall
amounts of 3 to 4 inches are possible from Thursday night through
Saturday night. Snowfall amounts of 6 inches are possible out the
Haines highway and up to 12 inches at White Pass with lower
amounts at lower elevations. Snow levels are forecast to rise to
around 2,500 feet or higher which could lead to a melting mountain
snowpack and introduce some nuisance flooding concerns. Rain at
White Pass is not out of the question. Rain over deep snow on top
of structures and rooftops could challenge load limits across
Upper Lynn Canal. Please stay tuned to local updates should
further flood bulletins be issued.']

Area: Inner Channels from Kupreanof Island to Etolin Island
Description:
['An atmospheric river will bring heavy rainfall, warming temperatures,
rising snow levels, and possibility of flooding across the south-
central Panhandle this weekend. A Flood Watch is now in effect
for the region.', 'Heavy rain begins Thursday night followed by a break on Friday.
Heavy rain then returns Friday night and persists into Saturday
night. The current forecast is for rainfall amounts of around 3
inches from Thursday night through Saturday night, with the
heaviest precipitation likeliest Friday night into Saturday night.
Snow levels are forecast to rise to 4,000 to 5,000 feet. Rain
along with a melting mountain snowpack will increase the risk of
minor flooding issues. Please stay tuned to local updates should
further flood bulletins be issued.']

Area: Lower Kuskokwim Valley; Kuskokwim Delta; Bristol Bay
Description:
['Two major storm systems and their associated fronts will bring
winter weather across Southwest Alaska. Snow accumulations of 1
to 4 inches are expected for most of Bristol Bay north of King
Salmon as two distinct fronts move ashore from south to north
beginning Thursday evening. Farther south, snow may mix with or
transition entirely to rain, leading to lower snowfall totals.
Some uncertainty remains regarding how and where this transition
will setup, although current thinking places this between Egegik
and Port Alsworth. Within this transition zone, the potential for
a short period of a wintry mix of freezing rain, sleet and snow
is possible. The wintry mix is expected to be brief and produce
only minimal ice accumulation before temperatures warm above
freezing behind the first front early Friday morning. However, the
timing of the changeover is still uncertain.']

Area: Middle Tanana Valley; Deltana and Tanana Flats; Upper Tanana Valley and the Fortymile Country; Denali; Eastern Alaska Range
Description:
['After several weeks of a cold and snowy pattern, a chinook
warming pattern will bring substantially warmer air into the
southern Interior from the Alaska Range up across the Tanana
Valley. Temperatures in the area are expected to rise into the
30s, and possibly even warmer near the Alaska Range. South winds
through the Alaska Range may reach into the 50-70 mph range.', 'Residents and interested parties should stay in tune and monitor
the latest forecasts at weather.gov/fairbanks and at our Twitter
and Facebook social media accounts for further updates.']

Area: Chukchi Sea Coast; Baldwin Peninsula and Selawik Valley; Northern and Interior Seward Peninsula; Southern Seward Peninsula Coast; Eastern Norton Sound and Nulato Hills; Yukon Delta; Lower Yukon Valley; Lower Koyukuk and Middle Yukon Valleys; Upper Kobuk and Noatak Valleys; Upper Kuskokwim Valley
Description:
['A moist Pineapple Express pattern will develop late Friday and
persist through early next week, which will come in several waves
of moisture from the Pacific. Currently, heavy snow looks to be
the main weather impact, although some locations may see brief
periods of rain and freezing rain, especially across the Lower
Yukon Valley and the Middle Kuskokwim Valley. In addition, expect
possible significant blowing and drifting snow as east winds
increase ahead of the front late Thursday and persist through late
Friday from Norton Sound north to Kotzebue Sound.', 'Residents and interested parties should stay tuned in and monitor
the latest forecasts at weather.gov/fairbanks and at our Twitter
and Facebook social media accounts for further updates.']

Area: Tutuila and Aunuu; Manua; Swains Island
Description:
['A weak tropical low (Invest 91P) south of Tutuila, will linger
near the territory through at least Thursday. This low may bring
showers, heavy at times, with gusty westerly winds. The Joint
Typhoon Warning Center (JTWC) does not see this tropical
disturbance intensifying while near the territory.', 'Westerly winds will be evident across north and west-facing
villages, and they are higher around downslope valleys, such as
the harbor area. Hence, a wind advisory has been issued throughout
the day today.', 'Furthermore, this unsettled weather will increase the potential
for flash flooding during this period. We will continue to
monitor for any flood advisories/warnings for American Samoa.']

Valley today. Gusty north winds combined with temperatures in the
teens and 20s across most of the area will result in wind chills

Area: Raft River Region; Franklin/Eastern Oneida Region; Bear Lake Valley
Description:
['For the Raft River region expect 1 to 3 inches of snow in general.
The Sublette mtns expect 3 to 5 inches. Winds will be breezy near
Idahome with gusts near 40 mph. Sweetzer summit will get around 2
inches of snow.', 'For the Franklin/Eastern Oneida region expect 1 to 5 inches of
snow. The Holbrook mtns look to get around 3 inches. Malad pass
around 2.5 inches of snow. Weston, Oxford, and Elkhorn peaks look
to get around 4 inches of snow. These peaks will see winds of
around 20 mph with higher gusts.', 'For the Bear Lake area, including Georgetown summit and Geneva
Summit, expect 1 to 4 inches of snow. Bern looks to get around 2.5
with Montpelier receiving around 2 inches. This Bear Lake area
could get slightly more snow than 1 to 4 inches. Currently, the
models show the Wasatch mtns getting the better snow and this
Bear Lake area being shadowed or downsloped. Overall, expect
winds less than 15 mph.']

Area: Upper Snake River Plain; Lower Snake River Plain; Eastern Magic Valley
Description:
['Expect around 1 to 3 inches of snow. The Eastern Magic Valley and
the Lower Snake Plain from Burley to Pocatello look to have
southerly flow ahead of a cold front this afternoon and will
likely see the lower end of snowfall of around 1 inch. This
southerly flow will likely warm the area, especially the I-84
corridor enough to produce rain as precipitation starts. Winds
will be southerly around 10 mph, possible as high as 15 mph. If
southerly winds are very light, temperatures will be colder and
more than 1 inch of snow will occur along the I-84 corridor. By
early evening, after cold front passage, expect westerly winds of
15 mph with gust near 20 to 25 mph mainly the I-84 corridor. For
the Upper Snake Plain expect around 2 to 3 inches of snow. The
eastern bench of the Lower Snake Plain could see around 3 inches
too. Also,there is a chance of convergence band after midnight
into early morning from Idaho Falls to Pocatello as well. The
chance is low currently. If this occurs the higher end of 3 inches
of snow is expected.']

Description:
['A quick-hitting storm system will bring snow to portions of
northern and eastern New Mexico through Thursday morning. The
highest snow totals of 2 to 4 inches are likely across the Sangre
de Cristo Mountains as well as the Sacramento Mountains. A quick
1 to 2 inches is also possible across the northeast plains with a
dusting of snow elsewhere across the east. Slick and icy roadways
may make for difficult travel conditions early Thursday morning,
particularly along mountain passes. Interstate 25 from Las Vegas
to Raton Pass, U.S. Highway 64/84, and U.S. Highway 412 may also
be impacted. Motorists are encouraged to slow down and allow extra
time for the morning commute.', 'For the latest road conditions visit nmroads.com or dial 5-1-1.']

Description:
['Significant reductions in visibility are expected in the higher
terrain of northeast Alabama and southern Middle Tennessee this
morning, due to a layer of very low stratus clouds across the region.
Locations above 1000 ft, including Lookout Mountain, Sand Mountain,
and the Cumberland Plateau, will experience widespread visibility
reductions to less than one quarter of a mile.', 'Motorists are urged to drive with extreme caution. Use low beams,
reduce driving speed, and allow for plenty of room between you and
other cars.', 'Visibility conditions will begin to improve around 10 AM CST.']

Description:
['Arctic high pressure will continue to build into the Mississippi
Valley today. Gusty north winds combined with temperatures in the
teens and 20s across most of the area will result in wind chills
in the single digits and teens this morning. A few slick spots are
possible this morning, mainly along and north of I-40, where some
light wintry precipitation fell overnight. Wind chills will drop
into the single digits and teens again tonight into Friday
morning.', "Take extra precaution during this morning's commute and dress
accordingly for the cold weather."]

Area: Scott; Campbell; Claiborne; Hancock; Morgan; Lee; Scott; Russell; Washington
Description:
['A cold front will push through the area this morning, ushering in
very cold temperatures. Rainfall will switch over to a light
wintry mix before changing over to light snow by early to mid
morning, before tapering off to flurries this afternoon. This may
produce slick spots on roadways, especially on bridges and
overpasses, just in time for the morning work commute. Snow
accumulations are expected to be an inch or less.', 'Slow down and use caution while traveling this morning.']

Description:
['With temperatures expected to drop across entire mid state region
into the 20s as early morning hours progress, patchy black ice
formation will be likely on elevated surfaces, bridges,
overpasses, and secondary shaded roadways through morning hours.
Treacherous travel conditions could be experienced. Sustained
north winds 10 to 20 mph with gusts approaching 30 mph at times
should help in drying major roadways out across our area,
but some slick spots could still remain. Exercise caution on area
roadways through morning hours today.']

Description:
['CCA', 'Steadily falling temperatures can be expected across much of Southeast
Texas today. Overnight tonight and on into early Friday morning, readings
are expected to approach freezing for parts of the area. Any lingering
rain areas will have the potential to interact with the near freezing
temperatures and transition into a wintry mix of freezing rain and sleet.', 'The main areas of concern are mainly south of Interstate 10, especially
the closer you get to the Edna-Bay City-Matagorda Bay area.', 'Monitor road conditions closely tonight through early tomorrow morning.']

Description:

through this morning. Snowfall will then dissipate over portions
of the central Texas Panhandle during the mid to late morning.', 'Snowfall, while light in accumulation, has led to reports of
occasional slick roadways. Drivers should be cautious during
their morning commute.', 'Wind chill values will be in the single digits above and below

freezing for the majority of the combined Panhandles.', 'Stay tuned to the developments of this winter system by visiting
our homepage at www.weather.gov/ama/']
